TypeScript is a strongly typed, class-based, and superset of JavaScript programming language that compiles to JavaScript. Developed by Microsoft, it focuses on enhancing developer productivity and code maintainability while targeting a wider audience than purely JavaScript. One of TypeScript's key features is Duck Typing, which is a different way of determining data types at runtime instead of compile-time as in JavaScript.

Duck Typing in TypeScript (and JavaScript) refers to the ability to treat an object as a specific type if it exhibits a given set of behaviors (i.e., methods or properties) that are typically associated with that type. This means you can test an object's capabilities at runtime rather than relying on its declared type.

In TypeScript, you can use interfaces, classes, or type-aliases to define custom types. If your program expects a certain set of methods or properties, you can create an interface that defines those requirements. For example:

```
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  greet(): void;
}
```

Now, you can check if an object conforms to this interface using an `is` assertion:

```typescript
function greetPerson(person: Person) {
  person.greet(); // TypeScript will verify that `person` has a `greet` method
}

const alice: Person = { name: 'Alice', age: 30 };
greetPerson(alice); // TypeScript will not complain because alice has `greet` method

const bob: any = { name: 'Bob' };
// TypeScript will throw an error because `bob` doesn't conform to the `Person` interface
greetPerson(bob); // TypeScript will complain, "Type 'any' is not assignable to type 'Person'."
```

Duck Typing in TypeScript (and JavaScript) allows you to leverage the object's behavior and properties to determine its type, without the need for explicit type annotations in some cases. It provides a more flexible and dynamic approach to type checking, as long as the object exhibits the expected behavior.

However, it's essential to note that Duck Typing may sometimes lead to runtime errors when the object's behavior doesn't match the expected behavior. It's crucial to design your code with clear interfaces or conventions to minimize this risk and maintain code readability and maintainability.

